  <div tabindex="-1" id="notebook" class="border-box-sizing">
    <div class="container" id="notebook-container">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Recommender-Systems">Recommender Systems<a class="anchor-link" href="#Recommender-Systems">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Recommender systems, also known as recommendation engines, provide for a more personalized web experience, be it on social media, shopping websites, or content providers such as Pandora and Netflix. There are two main types of recommender systems. There are those that employ content-based filtering and those that involve collaborative filtering. Content-based filters provide recommendations based on item characteristics. An example is where a recommendation for an item is made based on similar items that a user has utilized before. On the other hand, Collaborative Filtering (CF) involves providing recommendations based on how users have responded to an item.
Collabrative filtering can be further broken down to memory-based collaborative filtering and model-based collaborative filtering. As the name suggests, memory-based collaborative filtering involves building a model from the full dataset. The method algorithms utilize similarity metrics such as Euclidean distance, Pearson correlation, and cosine similarity to calculate user-item matches. In contrast, model-based collaborative filtering employs algorithms that extract information from the dataset that is then used to build a model to predict a user's rating for an item. In general, model-based CF tends to be less resource intense and better performing than memory-based CF algorithms, albeit harder to implement.
In this analysis, I will be exploring the use of model-based CF to build a movie-recommendation engine based on the 100k movie ratings MovieLens dataset.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Model-based-collaborative-filtering">Model-based collaborative filtering<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-based-collaborative-filtering">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The model-based CF algorithm used in this analysis involves matrix factorization of the user-item matrix. The idea is to characterize the original matrix as the product of two low-rank matrices, and use these to discover latent features that influence the user-item interaction. When trying to find latent features, an assumption is made that the number of latent features is smaller than the number of users, as well as the number of items. This makes intituitive sense since it is the commonality of features between users that allows us to be able to recommend items to one user based on the ratings of another.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Matrix-factorization">Matrix factorization<a class="anchor-link" href="#Matrix-factorization">&#182;</a></h3><p>If <strong>R</strong> is the <em>M x N</em> user-item matrix, we can approximate  <strong>R</strong> as the product of two low-rank feature matrices. <strong>P</strong> (<em>M X K</em>) is the factor matrix for users and <strong>Q</strong> (<em>N x K</em>) is the factor matrix for items (movies, in this case). <em>K</em> is the number of latent features</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$ \qquad  \mathbf{R} \in \mathbb{R} ^{M \times N}; \quad$  \mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R} ^{M \times K}; \quad  \mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R} ^{N \times K}; \quad   \mathbf{R} \approx \mathbf{\hat{R} } = \mathbf{P^{T}.Q} \qquad \text{(1)} $$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The cost function can be expressed as the sum of squared errors</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ J = \sum_{(u, i) \in K}(R_{u, i} - \hat{R_{u, i} })^{2} } \qquad \text{(2)} $$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To avoid overfitting, we can introduce a regularization term to the cost function. $\lambda$ is the regularization parameter</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ J = \sum_{(u, i) \in K}(R_{u, i} - \hat{R_{u, i} })^{2} + \lambda(||P_{u}||^{2} + ||Q_{i}||^{2})} \qquad \text{(3)}  $$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The goal then is to minimize on the cost function. To do this, we take partial derivatives with respect to $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ and set both derivatives to zero. Since we have two unknowns, $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$, we will use the Alternating Least Squares (ALS) technique to get the estimates for $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$. In this technique, we fix $\mathbf{Q}$ to get an estimate for $\mathbf{P}$ and then fix $\mathbf{P}$ to get an estimate for $\mathbf{Q}$. This is done for several iterations until there is little to no change to the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE), which is what we will use to evaluate for convergence.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The cost functions to minimize for each unknown are given by:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ J(p_{u}) = (r_{u} - p_{u}Q)W_{u}(r_{u} - p_{u}Q)^{T} + \lambda p_{u}p_{u}^{T} } \qquad \text{(4)} $$<p></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ J(q_{i}) = (r_{i} - Pq_{i})W_{i}(r_{i} - Pq_{i})^{T} + \lambda q_{i}q_{i}^{T} } \qquad \text{(5)}  $$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>$ \mathbf{W_{u} } \in \mathbb{R} ^{M \times M}$ and $ \mathbf{W_{i} } \in \mathbb{R} ^{N \times N}$ are weights that we use to penalize those items that are not rated so that the model depends wholly on the rated items. $\mathbf{W}$ is defined as:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$ \mathbf{W_{ui} } = 
\begin{cases}
0  & \text{if }r_{ui}=0\\
1 & \text{else}\\
\end{cases}$$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>and the update rules for the two unknowns are given as:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ p_{u} = A_{u}^{-1}V_{u}
\qquad \text{where }
A_{u} = QW_{u}Q^{T} + \lambda n_{u}E \text{;} \quad V_{u}=QW_{u}r_{u} }
\qquad \text{(6)}
$$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$\mathbf{ q_{i} = A_{i}^{-1}V_{i}
\qquad \text{where }
A_{i} = P^{T}W_{i}P + \lambda n_{i}E \text{;}\quad V_{i}=P^{T}W_{i}r_{i} }
\qquad \text{(7)}
$$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>$\mathbf{n_{u} }$  is a count of how many items each user rated while $\mathbf{n_{i} }$ is a count of how many users rated each item. $ \mathbf{E} \in \mathbb{R} ^{K \times K}$ is an identity matrix</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Equations 6 and 7 are of the general form $\mathbf{ x=A^{-1}V }$ where $\mathbf{A}$ is a matrix and $\mathbf{V}$ is a vector. This equation can be solved by doing an LU decomposition of the matrix $\mathbf{A}$ followed by forward and backward substitution so as to solve for  $\mathbf{x}$</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To evalute the algorithm, we calculate the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) where <strong>N</strong> is the total number of user-item pairs</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
$$ \mathbf{ RMSE = \sqrt{ { {1}\over {N} } \sum_{i=1}^{N}(R_{i} - \hat{R_{i} })^{2} } } \qquad \text{(8)} $$
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

</ul>

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1">#Obtain the training and test datasets using cross-validation</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">cross_validation</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="n">cv</span>
<span class="n">train_data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.25</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1">#Create a training and test matrix</span>
<span class="c1">#train_matrix = sparse.dok_matrix((num_users, num_movies), dtype=float)</span>
<span class="n">train_matrix</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">num_users</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">num_movies</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">train_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">itertuples</span><span class="p">():</span>
    <span class="n">user</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">movie</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">user</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">num_users</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">continue</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">movie</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">num_movies</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">continue</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">train_matrix</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">user</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">movie</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rating</span>

<span class="c1">#test_matrix = sparse.dok_matrix((num_users, num_movies), dtype=float)</span>
<span class="n">test_matrix</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">num_users</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">num_movies</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">test_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">itertuples</span><span class="p">():</span>
    <span class="n">user</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">movie</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">user</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">num_users</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">continue</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">movie</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">num_movies</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">continue</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">test_matrix</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">user</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">movie</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rating</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1">#Initialize the various variables</span>
<span class="c1">#K are the latent features, lmbda is the regularlization</span>
<span class="c1">#parameter lambda and &quot;iterations&quot; denotes the number of iterations</span>
<span class="c1">#to perform to convergence</span>
<span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">train_matrix</span>
<span class="n">T</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">test_matrix</span>

<span class="n">M</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span>
<span class="n">K</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">3</span>
<span class="n">lmbda</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.1</span>
<span class="n">iterations</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">50</span>
<span class="n">P</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rand</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">M</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">K</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">Q</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rand</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">N</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">K</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1">#This function calculates the RMSE. A penalty is imposed where we have an estimated rating</span>
<span class="c1">#but no actual rating in R. The penalty is imposed by multiplying by W</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">calcRMSE</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">W</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">rmse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">pow</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">W</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">))),</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">))</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">rmse</span>    
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To obtain the update rules, we take the derivatives of P and Q, and alternately update each factor as we fix the other. This is known as <strong>Alternate Least Squares</strong>. To avoid overfitting, a regularization term is introduced to the square error where lambda is the regularization parameter.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[12]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1">#Establish update rules</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">updateRules</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">K</span><span class="p">):</span>
    
    <span class="c1">#Get the training weight matrix which will contain a 1 if a movie was rated and 0 if not</span>
    <span class="n">W</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">W</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    <span class="n">W</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    
    <span class="c1">#Get the test weight matrix</span>
    <span class="n">Z</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">T</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">Z</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">T</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    <span class="n">Z</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">T</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    
    <span class="n">errors_T</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span> <span class="c1">#To store training RMSE</span>
    <span class="n">errors_TT</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span> <span class="c1">#To store test RMSE</span>
    <span class="n">E</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">eye</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">K</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># This is a K x K identity matrix</span>
    
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">xrange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">iterations</span><span class="p">):</span>
        
        <span class="c1">#Update for P with fixed Q</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">u</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Wu</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">enumerate</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">W</span><span class="p">):</span> <span class="c1">#Wu corresponds to the ratings by each user</span>
            <span class="n">num_mov</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count_nonzero</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wu</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1">#Count of how many movies each user rated</span>
            <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">num_mov</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
                <span class="n">num_mov</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="c1"># This is to guard against zero counts which would make the matrices to be singular</span>
            <span class="c1">#The least squares solution</span>
            <span class="c1">#Note that np.diag(Wu) takes the binary representation of each user (1, 0 if rated or not rated)</span>
            <span class="c1">#and converts into a diagonal array</span>
            <span class="n">matrix</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Q</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diag</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wu</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">))</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">lmbda</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">num_mov</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">E</span>
            <span class="n">vector</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Q</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diag</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wu</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">u</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">))</span>
            <span class="c1">#Factorize the matrix using LU decomposition, and then solve for P using</span>
            <span class="c1">#forward and backward substitution</span>
            <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">u</span><span class="p">,:]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">linalg</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">solve</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">matrix</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">vector</span><span class="p">)</span>
        
        <span class="c1">#Update for Q with fixed P. Steps are duplicated</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">v</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Wv</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">enumerate</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">W</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">):</span>
            <span class="n">num_users</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count_nonzero</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wv</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1">#Count of number of users that rated movie v</span>
            <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">num_users</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
                <span class="n">num_users</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
            <span class="n">matrix</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">P</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diag</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wv</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">)))</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">lmbda</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">num_users</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">E</span>
            <span class="n">vector</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">P</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diag</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Wv</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="n">v</span><span class="p">]))</span>
            <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">v</span><span class="p">,:]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">linalg</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">solve</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">matrix</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">vector</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
        <span class="c1">#Calculate RMSE for both the training and the test data</span>
        <span class="c1">#note that we use the P and Q trained on the training data</span>
        <span class="c1">#to test for generalization using the test data</span>
        <span class="n">errors_T</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">calcRMSE</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">W</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="n">errors_TT</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">calcRMSE</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Z</span><span class="p">))</span>
        
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">errors_T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">errors_TT</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>

<span class="n">P_pr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q_pr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">training_err</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_err</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">updateRules</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">T</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">P</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">K</span><span class="p">)</span>
